Title: Turkish Pipe
Description:
Complete bowl, broken at shank. Blackened at inner rim. Surface spalling on one side. Lily-shaped bowl with thick everted lip, outer rim with series of vertical striations. Double groove below lip, with ogee stamps superimposed below. Keel forms triangular decorative reinforcement with four convergent bands of wedge-shaped stamps; three pendent ogee stamps on front of bowl above reinforcement.

Weak red fabric (10R 5/3) with red slip (10R 4/8).

cf. MC 1290, 1296 and 1298. Sarachane Type VIII.

The findspot recorded for this object is not its original context. The object was found during cleaning of collapsed fill from the northern scarp of the trench, which had fallen down as a result of heavy rain during the previous winter.

Title: Basket 0
Description:
ΒΘ West is located at K/1,18–2/20,3/18. Excavation of this area continues the work first begun in 2008. 

The record of this season's excavations was written digitally in the field, and supplemented by hundreds of digital photographs (2013.15.0001-0714). These photographs document the excavation of each basket, as well as all pottery recovered from each basket before it was processed and lotted. The field notes were then copied into paper notebooks (ΒΘ XVIII, pp. 3401-3600, ΒΘ XX, pp. 3801-3879), supplemented there by additional black and white photographs, cross-sections, and plans. A table of contents for the notebook, a catalog of coins and finds from this season, and an index have been included with the final report stored in the Stoa of Attalos. 

Nomenclature for Byzantine rooms, walls, and architectural features will continue to be used in the same manner as in previous excavation seasons. See ΒΘ XVIII, p. 3422 for the beginning of season plan labeled with room numbers, wall numbers, excavation areas, and cross-sections.

The 2013 season will focus on six excavation areas within ΒΘ West: Rooms 2, 3, and 4 will continue to be excavated, and high fill around these rooms will be divided into the North Baulk, the Eastern Section, and the Southern Section. See the beginning of season plan for further clarification of this season's excavation areas, indicated in green, and digital photographs 2013.15.0003, .0005, .0007, and .0011.

Excavation of the North Baulk continues work started in 2012, and is divided into Western and Eastern Sections. The Western Section (K/9,11-3/1,2) includes a small portion of the Animal Pit excavated mainly in 2009 and 2010. The Eastern Section (K/12,18-3/3,9) is composed of two primary areas (Area I to the west, Area II to the east), along with two control baulks (μάρτυρες) separating the primary areas and a baulk separating ΒΘ East and West.

The Eastern Section will focus on the removal of fills adjacent to the eastern boundary of ΒΘ West, which is defined by Modern Concrete Foundation (MCF) 5. The Eastern Section will be divided into a Northeastern Area (K/13,16-3/7,11) and Southeastern Area (K/11,13-3/9,15).

The Southern Section (K/1,11-3/10,18) will continue work from the 2011 field season.

Fieldwork began with a thorough cleaning of the trench, including the removal of a substantial collapse of fill from the northern scarp of the trench, which was the result of an unusually heavy rainfall in February 2013. The results of these activities, as well as all future cleaning operations and their out-of-context finds, are recorded in Basket 0.

Title: Southern Section; Southwestern Area; Level 1
Description:
Open basket to investigate an area of high fill in the southwestern portion of the Southern Section. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring 3.35 m. east to west and 2.15 m. north to south, at its greatest extent.

The light brown fill is moderately compact, with inclusions of stone, tile, glass, and bone. There is a concentration of tile and large stone in the northwestern corner of the excavation area, consisting primarily of broken roof and floor tiles, and stones roughly 10-15 centimeters in diameter.

After the first pass, the tile and stone concentration remains localized to the northwestern corner of the excavation area, and we close to remove the tile and stone in a separate context (Basket 6).

Title: North Baulk; Western Section; Level 1
Description:
Open basket to begin removal of the westernmost portion of the North Baulk, which had been left unexcavated during the 2012 season. The fill had been isolated in 2012 because of animal bones visible within the scarp, likely a continuation of the Animal Pit (see ΒΘ Lots 96-101, 129-130, 236-238, and 409).

The excavation area is rectangular in shape, measuring approximately 0.50 m. northeast to southwest, and 1.75 m. northwest to southeast. The fill is greyish brown in color and moderately compact. Inclusions: small and medium sized stones, tile, small flecks of charcoal and plaster, including a large piece of plaster with a smooth surface (ca. 11 x 14 cm.).

As we descend with successive passes, we come down on patches of silty fill in the northwest portion of the excavation area, similar to the fill that surrounded the Animal Pit. We close basket.

Title: Eastern Section; Northeastern Area; Level 1
Description:
Open basket to begin investigation of fill in the Northeastern Area of the Eastern Section. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring 3.35 m. northeast to southwest and 2.50 m. northwest to southeast, at its greatest extent.

The northwestern portion of the excavation area had been excavated in previous seasons (2012 Basket 109 and 2009 Basket 66), but approximately two thirds of the area (more specifically, the eastern and southern portions) is located directly below the spread footing of MCF 5, and was never excavated after the removal of the spread footings. During the 2009-2011 excavation seasons, the unexcavated area served as the location for the supervisor's desks.

The light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of tile, bone and flakes of charcoal. As we remove fill, we expose more of the western face of MCF 5, which forms the eastern extent of the basket. Successive passes reveal no change in the composition of the fill, and we close arbitrarily.

Title: Southern Section; Southwestern Area; Level 2a; Tile Concentration
Description:
Open basket to investigate the tile and stone concentration in the northwestern corner of Southwestern Area. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 1.25 m. east to west and 1 m. north to south, at its greatest extend.

The light brown fill is moderately compact, with inclusions of tile, stone, shell, bone, glass and glass slag, and charcoal.

Successive passes indicate that the tile is located primarily in the western portion of the excavation area, while large stones are found in the east. We remove the tile, although some adhere to the concrete of Modern Wall 7 and cannot be removed. 

The tiles consist of many broken roof cover and pan tile fragments, along with wall and floor tile fragments. We clean, sort, and photograph the tile fragments, before looking for joins. 

After removing the tiles, we leave the large stones in situ and close.

Title: Eastern Section; Southeastern Area; Level 1
Description:
Open basket to investigate fill in the Southeastern Area of the Eastern Section. The excavation area is roughly triangular in shape and measures 4.50 m. north to south and 2.25 m. east to west.

The grey-brown fill is moderately compact, with significant quantities of ash, and inclusions of pebbles, small stones, tile, bone and charcoal. 

During the first pass the excavators observe that in the western side of the excavation area, adjacent to Wall 13, the fill has no ash, and is light yellowish brown in color, rather than grey-brown. The proximity of this fill to Wall 13 suggests the possibility that it could be its foundation trench.

In the southern end of the excavation area, we reveal a concentration of medium sized stones, which could perhaps be the top of a wall.

We close basket after one pass, to excavate the area with the yellowish brown fill in a separate context (Basket 14).

Title: Southern Section; Northeastern Area; Level 1a; Compact Fill
Description:
Open basket to remove an area of moderatly compact fill, higher in elevation than the surrounding fill. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring 1.30 m. southeast to northwest and 1.15 m. southwest to northeast.

The brown fill is moderately compact, with inclusions of small stone, tile, plaster, bone, glass, metal, and metal slag. On the eastern side of the basket we come down on the rubbly fill, which we isolate and leave in situ. After successive passes on the moderately compact we reach the level of surrounding fill without change. Close.

Basket 11 is located directly below the spread footing of Modern Concrete Foundation 6, which was removed after the 2008 excavation season. Fill in this area has not been excavated since the removal of the spread footing.

Title: Southern Section; Northeastern Area; Level 1b; Rubbly Fill
Description:
Open basket to investigate an area of high fill in the Northeastern Area of the Southern Section. The area is roughly circular in shape, measuring 1.10 m. north to south and 0.75 m. east to west, at its greatest extent. 

Similar to Basket 11, Basket 12 is located directly below the spread footing of Modern Concrete Foundation 6, which was removed after the 2008 excavation season. Fill in this area has not been excavated since the removal of the spread footing.

The brown fill is very loose and grainy, with much tile and coarse ceramic. The excavator also notes bone, charcoal, glass, glass slag, and metal slag, along with small olive green flakes within the fill.

After several passes, we bring the excavation area to the level of surrounding fill and close basket.

Title: Room 2; Eastern Section; Southern Area; Level 2
Description:
After taking the hypocaust tiles (ΒΘ 142 and ΒΘ 143) in Basket 9, we divide the high fill at the eastern end of Room 2 into northern and southern areas. We begin investigation of the Southern Area in Basket 13. The eastern and southern boundaries of the excavation area are defined by Walls 18 and 14. The excavation area measures ca. 0.80 m. east to west and 1.60 m. north to south.

The light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of tiles, small stones, and apricot-sized plaster chunks. With successive passes we expose more of the western face of Wall 18, and the fill becomes more compact and contains more plaster chunks. We descend upon grapefruit sized stones in the center of the excavation area, and close.

Title: Eastern Section; Southeastern Area; Level 2a; Light Brown Fill
Description:
Open basket to investigate fill east of and adjacent to Wall 13. The excavation area is roughly rectangular, measuring ca. 2.00 m. north to south and 0.25 m. east to west.

The light brown fill is moderately compact, with few inclusions of small stone and ceramic. We attempt to define a boundary between the light brown fill excavated within this basket and the greyish brown fill to the east, but the excavator does not find a distinct change. Successive passes indicate that the light brown fill extends further to the south and east, and is unlikely to be a foundation trench for Wall 13. We close to investigate the greyish-brown fill to the south and east.

Title: Room 2; Eastern Section; Southern Area; Level 3
Description:
Open basket to continue investigation of the Southern Area. The excavation area measures ca. 0.90 m. east to west and 1.80 m. north to south.

The light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of bone, glass, charcoal and plaster. As we take passes, we expose more of the cluster of stone in the center of the basket, which forms a rough line between the southern pier of Wall 16 and the western face of Wall 18. The excavator reveals a concentration of ash in the southeast corner of the basket, which is also visible in the disturbed fill below and to the south of the excavation area. 

We divide the area into two regions, separated by the line of stone in the center of the basket, in order to investigate whether the stones are a purposefully built architectural feature. We close and reopen on Level 4a, the fill on the northern side of the cluster of stones, in Basket 30.

Title: Eastern Section; Southeastern Area; Level 2b1; Mixed Grey and Light Brown Fill
Description:
Open basket to continue investigation of fill in Southeastern Area. After taking passes on the light brown fill east of and adjacent to Wall 13 in Basket 14, we now focus our efforts on the grey-brown fill to the south and east of Basket 14, which constitutes the majority of the Southeastern Area. The excavation area measures ca 4.60 m. north to south and 2.25 m. east to west at its greatest extent.

The grey-brown fill is moderately compact, with a significant amount of ash and charcoal flakes. Inclusions: stone, tile, bone, marble, metal, and metal slag.

We continue to define the western face of Modern Concrete Foundation (MCF) 5 as we descend, as well as more of the large classical block in the northeastern corner of the basket.

The excavator notes a significant concentration of tile, bone and plaster along the eastern boundary of the basket, which was cut by MCF 5. The plaster includes small pieces with a flat surface, which we leave in situ.

In the southern portion of the excavation area, we come down on more of the light brown fill, and also small pockets of sandy fill within the light brown. The small concentration of stone, which was revealed in Basket 7, does not continue. We remove it in this basket.

We close after one pass, with mixed fill (light brown to the west, grey-brown to the east) still characterizing the majority of the excavation area.

Title: Room 4; Western Section; Level 1
Description:
Open basket to begin investigation of fill in Room 4, last excavated in Basket 96 of the 2012 season. We divide the room in half along its north-south axis, and open basket on the western half of the room.

The 2012 excavation season ended with the removal of the thick layer of loose rubbly fill that covered the entire room. The removal of this layer exposed the stone slab in the center of the room, and moderately packed fill around it, which had a gentle downward slope towards the stone slab in the center. See 2012 ΒΘ West End of Season Report, pg. 6, for more information on the 2012 stratigraphy in Room 4.

The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring ca. 1.45 m. east to west by 2.80 m. north to south. It is bordered on the west by Wall 12, on the north and south by Walls 14 and 9, respectvely. The eastern portion of the excavation area cuts across the large marble block that lies in the center of Room 4, first exposed in Basket 80 of the 2012 season.

The light brown fill is moderately packed with inclusions of bone and glass. The excavators find a bronze coin along the eastern face of Wall 12, which may be modern. While we wait for conservation to clean the coin, we close after one pass in order to minimize the potential repercussions.

Description:

Title: Eastern Section; Northeastern Area; Level 3
Description:
Open basket to continue excavating the Northeastern Area of the Eastern Section. The basket is roughly triangular in shape, measuring 2.80 east to west by 4.40 m. north to south.

The grayish brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of charcoal, bone, plaster, tile, chunks of mudbrick and golf ball to grapefruit sized stones. As we take passes, we continue to expose the western face of MCF 5.

Successive passes reveal stone in line with the southern trajectory of Wall 22, including a nicely preserved columnar grave monument. The excavators also note a soil change in the fill between Walls 18 and 22, from moderately compact grey-brown to loose and rubbly.

Immediately to the south of the basket is a small and thin patch of concrete (ca. 0.60 x 0.55 m.) that spilled out into the fill to the west during the pouring of MCF 5. We remove the concrete and fill below out of basket, revealing more of the large classical block at the southern end of the excavation area, as well as other roughly faced stones that are likely a southern continuation of Wall 18.

Close after several passes.

Title: Room 2; Eastern Section; Southern Area; Level 5
Description:
Open basket to continue excavation of the Southern Area. After investigating the fill north and south of the stone cluster in separate baskets and removing the stone cluster in Basket 34, Level 5 again encompasses the entire Southern Area.

The moderately compact fill is generally light brown in color. Inclusions: charcoal, ash, plaster flecks.

In the southwest portion of the excavation area, the fill is light brown to orange in color and includes a patch of mudbrick. In the eastern portion of the excavation area, adjacent to the western face of Wall 18, we take the two patches of ash left in situ at the close of Basket 34. The ash continues to the east, under the course of stones that may be the lowest course of Wall 18 (see digital photo 2013.15.0054).

In this same area, the excavator removes a medium-sized stone (ca. 15 cm. in length) and reveals a small empty space below part of Wall 18. Within the space more stone is visible, which may have been placed below Wall 18 as part of a leveling operation before the construction of the wall. The placement of the stones visible in the empty space is irregular and without coursing.

Successive passes reveal more of the same light brown moderately compact fill, with flecks and small patches of ash and charcoal throughout. Close and reopen in Basket 44.

Title: North Baulk; Eastern Section; Area 1; Level 1

The light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: ash, charcoal, flecks of plaster, bone, glass, metal and glass slag, tile, shell and small stones.

As we descend, we reveal more of the eastern face of Wall 18 at the western limit of the excavation area. In the center of the excavation area, against the northern scarp of trench ΒΘ, we come down on several roughly faced stones, two of which are intersecting at a right angle. The trajectory of one group of stones is parallel to Walls 18 and 22, but far enough east that it cannot be part of either of these walls. The elevation of these stones is roughly the same as the highest preserved course of Wall 18.

Title: Room 2; Eastern Section; Southern Area; Level 7
Description:
After taking the moderately compact fill from the Southern Area of the Eastern Section of Room 2 in Basket 44, we open on the rubbly fill underneath. The excavation area is irregular in shape measuring ca. 1.50 m. north to south by ca. 0.80 m. east to west.

The rubbly fill is loose and pebbly throughout. Inclusions: ash, bone and charcoal. A high concentration of ash is present in the northern portion of the excavation area and contains inclusions of bronze, chunks of charcoal and iron slag. Successive passes continue to reveal courses of Walls 14 and 16 as we descend.

In the southeastern corner of the basket, at the intersection of Walls 18 and 14, we find a disturbance of modern concrete mixing with the lowest courses of Wall 18. It is likely part of the spread footing from Modern Concrete Foundation 6, and it appears that several of the stones adjacent to this wall are part of this modern concrete disturbance. We chip away at the concrete, but leave much in situ, lest we lose parts of Wall 18 while removing the concrete disturbance.

We close upon reaching the approximate level of the same rubbly fill in the rest of Room 2 to the west.

Title: Eastern Section; Southeastern Area; Level 2b2; Light Brown Fill
Description:
Open basket to continue removal of fill in the Southeastern Area, most recently excavated in Basket 20. We limit the excavation area to areas of higher fill in the south, which had been left at the close of Basket 20. The excavation area is roughly triangular in shape, measuring ca. 2.55 m. north to south and 0.85 east to west. We exclude the roughly circular area of sandy fill and the plaster and charcoal concentration found during Basket 20. 

The moderately compact fill is mostly light brown in color with patches of ashy grey-brown. Inclusions: charcoal, bone and metal. The excavator finds a nail near the eastern face of Wall 13, which may be modern. We save the nail for lotting.

After taking a pass on the moderately compact light brown, we expand to the east to investigate the plaster and charcoal concentration. We find more pottery than in the light brown fill, as well as metal debris, charcoal and painted plaster with a flat surface. We close to excavate this area and the sandy fill in separate contexts (Baskets 60 and 58, respectively).

Title: North Baulk; Eastern Section; Area 1; Level 2
Description:
Open basket to continue removal of fill from Area 1 of the Eastern Section of the North Baulk. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 4.30 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 1.30 m. southwest to northeast at its greatest extent. The light brown fill is moderately compact, with inclusions of charcoal, ash, tile, shell, bone and glass. 

As we take passes, we continue to expose more of the group of stones first revealed in Basket 42. We reveal two courses on one face of a roughly square feature, which follows the north-south alignment of Walls 18 and 22. Although one side of this square feature (facing west) is roughly faced with worked stone, a second side (facing south) is less regular, so far composed of unfaced stone, along with broken tile and smaller stone. The northern extent of the square feature is concealed by the northern scarp of the trench.

To the north of the roughly faced course of stones, a large square stone abuts this square feature at a right angle. A rough line of unfaced stones proceeds to the southwest from this square stone, not yet reaching Wall 18.

After successive passes we bring the fill down to the level of fill immediately to the southwest, which was directly below the course of Wall A. This fill had only been excavated in one basket since the removal of Wall A in 2008 (see 2008 Basket 50 and 2011 Basket 50).

We close and reopen in Basket 54, expanding the excavation area to include the fill below Wall A to the south.

After successive passes we come down on more compact fill. We close once the looser fill is completely removed.

Title: North Baulk; Eastern Section; Area 1; Level 4a; Investigation of Concrete Intrusion
Description:
Open basket to investigate fill surrounding a hole associated with a modern concrete intrusion in the vicinity of Wall 18. Cleaning around the concrete indicates that it continues northward below the fill in Area 1.

The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 0.70 m. north to south by ca. 0.85 m. east to west.

Around the hole, the light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: small plaster chunks, ash, charcoal. In the southern part of the excavation area, immediately above and around the concrete, we find modern plastic debris. A small coin (ΒΘ-217) was found during out of basket cleaning in this same area, shortly before we opened the basket. 

We expose a smoothly faced stone at the western edge of the basket, which runs perpendicular to the stone feature north of the basket.

With successive passes we expose more of the hole and concrete, which expands out into a large open area, approximately 55 cm. below the current level of the surrounding fill. The open cavity continues under Wall 18 to the west.

After exposing all of the concrete intrusion, clearing the fill around it, and determining the full extent of the cavity, we close.

Title: Room 4; Western Section; Level 6a
Description:
Open basket to investigate the loose fill surrounding the pithos, which could potentially be associated with the structure's construction. The excavation area is roughly semicircular in shape, measuring ca. 1.90 m. north to south and 0.35 m. east to west.

The light brown fill has inclusions of bone, tile, stone and flecks of charcoal. The excavator reports that the loose fill is confined to a small area near the center of the excavation area, and elsewhere there is no significant difference between the fill next to the pithos and the rest of the fill in the Western Section. 

Fill in this basket continues to have a high quantity of tile debris, but we have found many similar concentrations throughout the investigation of the Western Section of Room 4 over the course of the season, and the presence of high quantities of tile debris does not represent a significant difference from fill in the rest of the room.

Upon determining that there is no significant difference in compaction, color, or content of the fill surrounding the pithos and that in the rest of the Western Section, we close.

Title: Southern Section; Northeastern Area; Eastern Extension; Fill Between Walls 8, 9, and 13
Description:
Open basket to investigate the small triangular area of fill surrounded by Walls 8, 9 and 13, most recently excavated in 2012 Basket 85. The excavation area measures ca. 2.05 m. north to south and 0.75 m. east to west.

The brown fill is loose and rubbly, similar in consistency to the fills found in Rooms 1 and 4, and below the Tile Surface South of Wall 9 (See ΒΘ Lots 389, 415, and 425). Inclusions: tile, bone, glass.

After successive passes, we come down on moderately compact light brown fill. We reveal more courses of Wall 13, but below Walls 8 and 9 we find fill with few stones, unlikely to be part of lower courses of the walls. The portions of Walls 8 and 9 adjacent to this excavation area are composed of small unfaced stone, unlike the handsomely faced stone of Wall 13. See 2012 Basket 85 and pp. 5-6 of the 2012 end of season report for more discussion of these walls.

With the loose rubbly fill removed, we close.

Title: Room 3; Level 1
Description:
With excavation of the Western Section of the North Baulk concluded in Basket 63, we are now prepared to investigate the remaining high fill comprising the northwestern corner of Room 3. This high fill extends from Wall 21 at the west to Wall 16 at the east, measuring ca. 3.90 m. The northern scarp of the trench defines the northern boundary of the excavation area (ca. 1 m. of high fill between the portion of Room 3 excavated in 2012 and the northern scarp of the trench).

The light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: glass slag, metal debris, tile, bone. As we take passes, we continue to expose the face Wall 16 at the eastern edge of the basket. 

At the west, we investigate the concentration of stone in the vicinity of Wall 21. The northern face of Wall 21 is well defined and continues westward past Wall 12, but the southern face of this wall is mostly obscured by a large scatter of stone and tile debris. Investigation of this debris reveals a second southern face, indicating that either Wall 21 is approximately 1.20 m. wide, has more than one phase, or that there are two walls on the north side of Room 3.

Successive passes indicate that we are well below the fragmentary door sill, which is clearly not in its original context. We remove the sill, which has indentations for doors on both sides. Below the sill, we come down on part of a large coarseware vessel. The excavator also finds many joining fragments of a bowl with poorly preserved glaze. The presence of these vessels suggests that we are finding a continuation of Deposit K 3:2.

We close to take the fill within the large coarseware vessel in a separate context.

Title: North Baulk; Eastern Section; Area 1; Level 5a
Description:
Open basket to investgate fill between the architectural feature in Area 1 and Wall 18. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring ca 1.00 m. north to south by ca. 0.15 m. east to west. sherds: 525
"classical black glaze": 24
Title: North Baulk; Eastern Section; Area 1; Level 5b
Description:
Open basket to continue removal of fill around the architectural feature in Area 1. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 2.15 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 1.70 m. northeast to southwest at its greatest extent.

The light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: small chunks of plaster, charcoal, ash, bone, metal slag, glass slag and glass. 

As we take passes, we continue to expose courses of the western face of Wall 24, which defines the eastern side of the architectural feature. The wall is composed of roughly faced stone and tile spolia with joints of fill.

In the southern part of the basket, 
we come down on a line of stone that may define the southern boundary of the architectural feature. Their alignment is perpendicular to Walls 18, 22 and 24, but at present the shape and composition does not prove that it is more than a small concentration of stone and tile that happens to be in the correct position to suggest a southern boundary of a square architectural feature.

Successive passes also reveal more of the northern side of the feature, and the fill begins to fall away in the northeastern corner of the feature, perhaps suggesting a continuation of the cavity to the east.

We close after several passes, with the level of fill the same as that in Area 2 to the east.

Title: Room 3; Level 2; Fill within Pithos
Description:
We open basket in Room 3 to take the fill within the coarseware vessel (later determined to be a pithos) exposed in Basket 71. The excavation area is roughly circular in shape with a diameter of 0.60 m.

In consultation with the excavation's Byzantine pottery specialist, Dr. Joanita Vroom, we save the fill within the pithos in several levels, recording the starting elevation of each level and photographing our progress as we descend in 3 cm. passes. In Level 0, we save the fill from against the southeastern face of Wall 23. All fill from the first two levels within the pithos is saved in Levels 1 and 2.

As we descend, Dr. Vroom determines that the vessel is a pithos. For this reason, she advises that we save only ca. 3 cm. of fill adjacent to the vessel wall in Levels 3, 4 and 5. In Levels 6 and 7, when the bottom of the pithos begins to be visible, we save all fill. Upon the removal of Level 7, the bottom of the pithos is fully exposed.

The light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: bone, charcoal, shell, small chunks of plaster and tile and apricot to grapefruit sized stones (ca. 10 cm. in diameter). The excavator notes several tile fragments and four medium sized stones (ca. 10 cm. by 10 cm.) in the fill of Levels 3-4. Levels 6 and 7 comprise fill with few inclusions.

After we take Level 7, we close to excavate the fill around the pithos in a separate context.

sherds: 2088

Title: Southern Section; Removal of Rubbly Fill in East
Description:
Open basket to remove the large area of loose rubbly fill that covers much of the eastern portion of the Southern Section. Due to heavy foot traffic and lack of excavation in previous seasons, the fill is removed in one large pass over the entire eastern half of the Southern Section, in an effort to begin future work in the area on firmer ground. The excavation area measures ca. 4.90 m. north to south by 3.05 m. east to west.

The brown fill is very loose and grainy, with inclusions of bone, shells, tile, stone, plaster and glass. Its consistency and inclusions are similar to the rubbly fills found in Rooms 1 and 4, and below the Tile Surface South of Wall 9, during the 2012 season (see ΒΘ Lots 389, 415, and 425). 

Below the loose rubbly we find a moderately compact light brown fill. In the center of the excavation area, however, the loose rubbly continues deeper, forming a distinctive circular pit, which we leave in situ. 

We extend the excavation area to the south, taking more loose rubbly until we reach the southern scarp of Trench ΒΘ. The excavators reveal a large area of moderately compact light brown fill, similar in appearance to large slabs of mudbrick. We leave this fill in situ.

At the north, close to the southern face of Wall 9, the loose rubbly fill continues further down into a small trench that was dug parallel to the wall- perhaps an unlined drainage channel?

With the loose rubbly fill removed, we close.

Title: North Baulk; Eastern Section; Area 1; Stone and Tile Debris
Description:
Open basket on the stone and tile debris left in situ after Basket 42, between the architectural feature, Wall 24, and the northern scarp of ΒΘ West. Based on the alignment of the larger stones, it seems likely that there is an eastern face to Wall 24, with the stone and tile debris against it. The basket is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 0.50 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 0.35 m. northeast to southwest.

We take the tile and stone debris in passes, gradually exposing the larger stones. The light brown fill is moderately compact with a high concentration of fist-sized stones and tile fragments. We find that the larger stones do not have worked facing, however, and there appears to be no clearly defined eastern side of Wall 24.

Since the stone and tile debris may in fact be part of the architectural feature (backfill behind the larger stones?), we close after two small passes and leave the majority of the debris in situ.

Title: Eastern Section; Northeastern Area; Level 5
Description:
Open basket to continue investigation of fill in the Northeastern Area. We limit the excavation area to the fill adjacent to the intersection of Walls 9 and 22, which at present is defined only by a few stones. The basket is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 3 m. north to south and ca. 1.60 m. east to west, at its greatest extent.

The light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: bone, metal slag and small chunks of plaster. We find one additional stone at the intersection of the walls, but their juncture remains scrappy. We also find a concentration of stone and tile debris near the eastern face of Wall 18, which may be related to the larger cluster of stone and tile on the opposite side of the same wall. We close after two passes, in order to bring the fill to the northeast down to the same level before the end of the excavation season.

Title: Room 3; Level 5
Description:
After exposing part of the yellowish-brown surface feature in the fill south of and adjacent to Wall 23, we open to continue investigating the extent of the feature to the east. The boundaries of the excavation area remain the same as Baskets 86 and 96.

Successive passes continue to reveal more of the surface feature. We find bits of charcoal on and embedded within the surface, along with stone and tile debris. The northern boundary of the surface is less uniform and definite than the boundary in the west, with an undulating border tapering off into the surrounding gray fill. The surface continues sloping downward to the eastern boundary of the excavation area. After defining the limits of the feature at the north and east, we remove the pithos and define the western boundary, which does not connect with Wall 23. The southern boundary is also not clearly defined. At several points it is close to the southern scarp, but there is no clear evidence that it continued southward into the portion of Room 3 excavated in 2012.

North of the surface feature, we scrape away at the moderately compact grey-brown fill and reveal  a glazed bowl, with large pieces of burnt wood in the vicinity. We also find four more coins during our investigation of fill above and around the surface, bringing the total number of coins found in Baskets 86, 96 and 100 to nine. We have also saved all tile fragments found during excavation of these baskets, and we recover an almost complete roof cover tile (ΒΘ 180) after washing and sorting the tiles.

With the pithos removed and the surface defined, we close due to end of season.

Description:
Open basket to continue removal of fill in the Northeast Area. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 3.45 m. northwest to southeast and ca. 2.95 m. northeast to southwest. 

The light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of bone, metal slag and small chunks of charcoal and plaster. As we take passes, we continue to expose the eastern face of Wall 22. After one pass, we come down to the level of fill immediately to the south, taken in Basket 94, and close due to end of season.

Title: Room 2; Control Baulk 2
Description:
Open basket to remove the high fill left after excavation in the Eastern and Central Sections of Room 2. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring ca. 1.50 m. north to south by 0.70 m. east to west.

The grey-brown fill is loose and rubbly, with the exception of a small area to the northern side of the basket, which at first is moderately compact but after the first pass comes down on the loose rubbly. Inclusions: bronze debris, metal and glass slag, charcoal, slag, tile and bone.

Once the area is brought down to the level of the surrounding fill, we close.
